Boil a full #kettle{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim and halve the @green beans{80}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

Trim and peel the @carrot{1}. Use the #peeler{} to peel long ribbons down the length of the carrot, stopping at the core.

Drain the @firm tofu{280%g} and chop into 2cm cubes. Pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

In a large #bowl{}, mix together the @Thai style spice mix{1%tsp}, @plain flour{1%tbsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Add the tofu to the bowl and toss to coat.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, fry the tofu until slightly crispy, ~{8-10%minutes}. Turn frequently to ensure it doesn't burn.

Transfer to a #plate{} lined with kitchen paper. Sprinkle over the lime zest and season again with salt and pepper.

While the tofu cooks, pour the boiling water from your kettle into a large #saucepan{} with 1/4 tsp salt on high heat.

Add the @egg noodle nests{2} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Wipe out the (now empty) frying pan and pop on medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

Once hot, add the green beans and carrot ribbons. Stir-fry until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the garlic and @red Thai style paste{50%g}, then fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @vegetable stock paste{1%tsp}, and @water{150%ml}. Cook until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, add the cooked noodles and tofu to the pan and mix to coat.

Add a splash of water to loosen if you feel it needs it, then taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Squeeze in some lime juice, then remove from the heat.

Share your red Thai style noodles between your #bowls{}.

Finish with a sprinkle of @chilli flakes{1}(sprinkled) and serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!

> Add less chilli flakes if you'd prefer things milder.